text: So Sweden is almost as high as the UK in covid deaths/capita last 7 days. But the restrictions have given us close to 0 cases of the seasonal flu: <https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/folkhalsorapportering-statistik/statistik-a-o/sjukdomsstatistik/influensa-veckorapporter/aktuell-influensarapport/|https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/folkhalsorapportering-statistik/statistik-a-o/sjukdoms[…]stik/influensa-veckorapporter/aktuell-influensarapport/> (Since November, 28 000 tests showed 3 cases of Influenza A and 6 cases of Influenza B). So clearly people are taking precautions, but covid spreads fast anyway.

(Since November, 28 000 tests showed 3 cases of Influenza A and 6 cases of Influenza B). So clearly people are taking precautions, but covid spreads fast anyway.

text: We're seeing the same thing all around the world. Basically the same picture in Denmark, and also in Australia, who have passed their flu season some time ago.

elements.text: We're seeing the same thing all around the world. Basically the same picture in Denmark, and also in Australia, who have passed their flu season some time ago.

text: Yes, but Denmark is somewhat successful in fighting covid (at <1/3 the current and total death rates compared to Sweden). Australia reported 0 covid deaths in the last 7 days and 1/28 of Sweden's total deaths. You would really expect Australia to have succeeded at fighting other diseases. But not Sweden, the UK, or Belgium
